":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Amisfield, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Amisfield, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Charteris","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, Scottish: from the city of  <i>Chartres</i> in N France;  see  Charters  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Charters","meanings":["Scottish (Kirkcudbrightshire) and northern English: habitational name of Norman origin from the French city of Chartres, named for a Gaulish tribe, recorded in Latin sources as the <i>Carnutes</i>, whose seat it was.","English: variant of   Chatters  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Charteris 5th of Amisfield and Drumgrey was born about 1415, in Amisfield, Dumfriesshire, Scotland as the son of The Fourth Robert of Amisfield Charteris. He had at least 1 son with Dama En Blanco. He died before 1473, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1415–before 1473":"umbes 1415–enne 1473","1415